Conclusion:
The clustering experiment was successfully performed using the SimpleKMeans algorithm in WEKA. The
soybean dataset, which contains information about different soybean plant conditions and diseases, was used
for this experiment. The algorithm grouped the 683 instances into 4 clusters using the Manhattan distance
measure based on the similarity among attribute values. The clustering results showed the cluster centroids,
number of instances in each cluster, and cluster distribution, which helped in understanding how the data was
organized into meaningful groups.Thus, the experiment demonstrates that K-Means clustering is an effective
unsupervised learning technique for identifying patterns and grouping similar data instances in a dataset.
